  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">213461_DFID NRC led - Recovery, Reintegration and Resilience (R3 Consortium)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">WV is part of consortia led by NRC with others being CARE, Relief International and Action Against Hunger that applied for the DFID ERR opportunity. Overall amount 22.5million. The programme is expected to be delivered through a consortium or other such grouping of organisations Organisations are welcome to propose the kind of structure that they feel would best address the challenges identified. The words &#x2018;consortium and consortia&#x2019; are used throughout to mean the delivery organisation but should not be taken to preclude other forms of organisational structure. with the overall objective to promote early recovery, build resilience and provide durable solutions to vulnerable populations across Afghanistan through integrated, multi-sectoral interventions. Target populations are those who would benefit from resilience-building and/or early recovery programming and could be but are not limited to: displaced populations and their host communities; returnees from neighbouring countries; displaced populations seeking to return to their area of origin; those affected by conflict or natural disasters such as drought. Consortia will be expected to propose activities that will address challenges associated with these populations, and to justify their rationale for the target population, geographic coverage and chosen activities through evidence-based analysis. It must be clear how the different activities complement one another and contribute to the overall objectives of the programme, and you should state the experience and expertise that each member of the consortium brings to the collective whole.
 
 
 
 Interventions can combine different facets of early recovery and resilience building activities for example essential basic service provision, such as access to water, with steps to address chronic humanitarian issues, such as food insecurity, with those that provide opportunity to build resilience and self-reliance, such as livelihood support, vocational training and market support. Likewise, for many IDPs and returnees in prolonged states of displacement, problems of access to land, landlessness and/or a lack of secure tenure as well as a lack of civil documentation are key obstacles to durable solutions. There are no prescribed approach and innovation is encouraged. However, it is important that activities are justified in addressing key challenges and their expected impact is clearly articulated through an evidence-based approach. It is also important that proposed activities champion a community-based approach and that mechanisms are in place to gather and take action on beneficiary feedback.</narrative>
  </description>
